The possible configurations and use-cases: - setStrictRequirements(true): Throw an exception for mismatching requirements. This is mostly useful in development environment. - setStrictRequirements(false): Don't throw an exception but return null as URL for mismatching requirements and log the problem. Useful when you cannot control all params because they come from third party libs but don't want to have a 404 in production environment. It should log the mismatch so one can review it. - setStrictRequirements(null): Return the URL with the given parameters without checking the requirements at all. When generating a URL you should either trust your params or you validated them beforehand because otherwise it would break your link anyway. So in production environment you should know that params always pass the requirements. Thus this option allows to disable the check on URL generation for performance reasons (saving a preg_match for each requirement every time a URL is generated).
trans-unit.target: 可能的配置和用例:-setStrictRequirements(true)。对不匹配的需求抛出一个异常。这在开发环境中很有用。-setStrictRequirements(false):不抛出异常,但返回空值。不抛出异常,但对不匹配的需求返回null作为URL并记录问题。当你不能控制所有的参数时很有用,因为它们来自第三方库,但又不想在生产环境中出现404。它应该记录不匹配的情况,以便人们可以检查它。-setStrictRequirements(null):返回带有给定参数的URL,完全不检查需求。当生成一个URL时,你应该相信你的参数,或者你事先验证了它们,因为否则它会破坏你的链接。所以在生产环境中,你应该知道参数总是通过需求。因此,这个选项允许为了性能原因而禁用URL生成的检查(每次生成URL时都要为每个需求保存一个preg_match)。
